-- CAC 40 Ends Little Changed; Safran, Valeo Shares Rise as Nexans Declines
-- David Altaner
-- 2010-07-28T16:13:12Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-28/french-stocks-advance-paced-by-eads-air-france-lvmh-valeo-also-rise.html

          
          
             France’s  CAC 40 Index  rose 3.96
points, or 0.1 percent, to close at 3,670.36 at 4:30 p.m. in
Paris. The  SBF 120 Index  gained less than 0.1 percent.  
 The following stocks are among the most active in the
French equity market today. Stock symbols are in parentheses
after company names.  
 Air France-KLM Group  (AF FP) gained 1.1 percent to 11.07
euros. Europe’s biggest airline reported its first quarterly
profit since 2008 on a one-time gain from its stake in flight-
reservations provider Amadeus IT Holding SA. Net income was 736
million euros ($957.4 million) in the three months ended June
30, compared with a year-earlier 426 million-euro loss.  
 Nexans SA  (NEX FP) dropped 8.5 percent to 51.25 euros, the
biggest decline since April 22. The world’s biggest maker of
cable and wires said profitability declined to 4 percent of
revenue in the first half from 5.3 percent a year earlier.  
 Rexel SA  (RXL FP) rallied 4.9 percent to 13.13 euros. The
electrical equipment distributor raised its forecast for 2010.  
 Safran SA  (SAF FP) rose 6.5 percent to 21.51 euros.
Europe’s second-biggest maker of aircraft engines raised its
outlook for 2010 and predicted net income will advance.  
 Valeo SA  (FR FP) rose 5.4 percent to 27.30 euros. France’s
second-largest auto-parts maker raised its full-year operating
margin forecast after recording first-half net income of 168
million euros as government-backed incentives spurred auto
production.  
